A: You can use the getBytes() method of the String class to convert a String to a byte array. The getBytes() method takes a Charset parameter, which you can use to specify the encoding. Here is an example:

```java
String str = "Hello, World!";
byte[] bytes = str.getBytes(StandardCharsets.UTF_8);
```

In this example, the string "Hello, World!" is converted to a byte array using UTF-8 encoding. The resulting byte array contains the binary representation of the string.

Please note that the getBytes() method does not create a new String object. It simply returns a byte array that represents the same sequence of characters as the original String.

Also, please note that the getBytes() method can throw a UnsupportedEncodingException if the named charset is not supported. If you are sure that the charset is supported, you can wrap the call to getBytes() in a try-catch block to handle this exception.

```java
try {
    byte[] bytes = str.getBytes(StandardCharsets.UTF_8);
} catch (UnsupportedEncodingException e) {
    // Handle the exception
}
```

This way, you can avoid the UnsupportedEncodingException from being thrown and your program will not crash if the specified charset is not supported.

